  "prompt": "How can you determine the molecular mass of ammonium?",
  "response": "To determine the molecular mass of ammonium (NH\u2084\u207a), you need to calculate the sum of the atomic masses of all the atoms in the ion. Here's the step-by-step process:\n\n1. **Identify the atoms in the ammonium ion**:\n   - Ammonium (NH\u2084\u207a) consists of **1 nitrogen (N) atom** and **4 hydrogen (H) atoms**.\n\n2. **Find the atomic masses of the elements**:\n   - The atomic mass of nitrogen (N) is approximately **14.01 atomic mass units (u)**.\n   - The atomic mass of hydrogen (H) is approximately **1.01 atomic mass units (u)**.\n\n3. **Calculate the total mass**:\n   - Mass of nitrogen (N): 1 \u00d7 14.01 u = **14.01 u**\n   - Mass of hydrogen (H): 4 \u00d7 1.01 u = **4.04 u**\n   - Total molecular mass of ammonium (NH\u2084\u207a): 14.01 u + 4.04 u = **18.05 u**\n\nThus, the molecular mass of ammonium (NH\u2084\u207a) is approximately **18.05 atomic mass units (u)**. Note that the charge (+1) does not affect the mass calculation.",
